So much success in the Trump White House, they can't even spell the word
By Chris Reeves  
Friday Jun 09, 2017 · 8:26 PM GMT
2017/06/09 · 20:26

No matter who is in the White House, it is a big deal to win the Presidential Academic Award. But for Kendra Frautnick, the award itself had a few problems.
From her Facebook post:
www.facebook.com/...
That time your 8th grade daughter earned the presidential award but sadly it's from the Trump administration and they spelled success wrong. And sent it to all of the graduating 8th graders across the country who earned this award. I wish this was fake news 
:(
That’s right. The president sent out a letter to award winners with an obvious misspelling. Success, a word many people in politics spell daily, is not a spelling bee level word. But for the Trump administration, it is apparently enough of a stranger than a spell check was in order.
This isn’t the first time the administration or their allies have been caught with bad press releases and statements. Just a few weeks ago, the White House release on their trip to the middle east was rife with errors. More recently, Secretary of State turned Governor candidate Kris Kobach issued out a statement using Kansas State letterhead with a glaring error as well.
Who needs editors, right? 
Don’t worry kids. Education really does matter. We promise.

What comes across in this “letter” is a powerful …
What comes across in this “letter” is a powerful statement about the role of education in Trump’s world:  (1) Two of the six sentences begin with “I”, and a third is “Melania joins me” which is just an token work-around so that there isn’t a third “I”; (2) There’s no salutation to clarify the confusion in the wording of the first sentence, which appears to be directed at to the school principal vs. the rest of the text which is clearly aimed at the individual winner of the award; (3) The emphasis is that the winners have achieved this recognition entirely by individually striving for knowledge and working to achieve success — and by inference, everyone else is a loser; and (4) no mention is made of teachers, principals and parents for creating and supporting a supportive environment for this child or any child to learn.  Does anyone reading this post have a copy of the letter that President Obama sent out each spring?
